\par \hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37 
Observables in RxJS provide a more powerful and flexible way to work with asynchronous data streams compared to promises. While promises represent a single future value, observables represent a sequence of values that arrive over time. Here are some reaso
\hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37 ns why you might choose observables over promises: 
\par \hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37 Streams of Data: Observables can emit m\hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37 
ultiple values over time, whereas promises represent only a single value. This makes observables suitable for representing streams of events, such as user inputs, server responses, or data updates over time. 
\par \hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37 
Cancellation: Observables support cancellation, which allows you to unsubscribe from a data stream when you no longer need it. This can help in scenarios where you want to stop receiving data or release resources when they're no longer needed, thus preven
\hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37 ting memory leaks and unnecessary processing. 
\par \hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37 T\hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37 
ransformation and Composition: Observables offer powerful operators for transforming, filtering, combining, and composing streams of data. These operators allow you to manipulate data streams in sophisticated ways, making it easier to implement complex as
\hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37 ynchronous logic. 
\par 
\par \hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37 
Lazy Evaluation: Observables are lazy by default, meaning that they don't start emitting values until someone subscribes to them. This can be useful for optimizing performance, especially in scenarios where you have multiple asynchronous
\hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37  operations but only need to execute them when necessary. 
\par 
\par \hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37 
Error Handling: Observables provide built-in error handling mechanisms, allowing you to gracefully handle errors that occur during asynchronous operations. Error handling in observables is integrated with the stream itself, making it easier to propagate a
\hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37 nd handle errors within the data flow. 
\par 
\par \hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37 Backpressure Handling: Observables support backpressure handling, which allows consumers to control the rate at which they receive data from a producer. Thi\hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37 
s can be important in scenarios where the producer emits data at a faster rate than the consumer can process it, helping to prevent overload and improve overall system stability. 
\par 
\par \hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37 
Overall, while promises are simpler and sufficient for many basic asynchronous operations, observables offer a more comprehensive and flexible approach to dealing with asynchronous data streams, especially in complex or interactive applications. RxJS prov
\hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37 ides a rich set of tools for working with observables, making it a popular c\hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37 hoice for managing asynchronous operations in JavaScript applications 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\cf6\lang9\langfe16393\kerning0\langnp9\insrsid11741607 \hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37 
Debouncing is a general programming technique that can be implemented in various ways, not limited to RxJS or even JavaScript. It involves creating a mechanism to delay the execution of a function until a certain amount of time has passed since the last i
\hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37 nvocation. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang9\langfe16393\kerning0\langnp9\insrsid11741607 \hich\af37\dbch\af31505\loch\f37 
debounceTime is a specific operator provided by the RxJS library. It's used within RxJS observables to debounce the stream of values emitted by the observable. 
